value.value: A portion of chlorenchyma tissue (PO:0005426) that is part of the plant ovary wall (PO:0005022) and is composed of mesophyll cells (PO:0004006).

definition.value: In some species, such as Arabidopsis, there may be a distinct subepidermal adaxial cell layer. The cells in the mesophyll layer(s) may not differentiate similar to the spongy and palisade cells found in the leaf mesophyll.

value.value: Multinucleate cell developed by a series of events involving kayokinesis but not cytokinesis of the initial feeding cell. The events are induced by root knot nematodes (e.g., Meloidogyne sp. ) entering the feeding cells (any cells) of the root vascular system.

Multinucleate cell developed by a series of events involving fusion with the neighboring dividing cells. The events are induced by cyst nematodes (e.g. Heterodera schachtii) entering the feeding cells (any cells) of the root vascular system.
A shoot system vascular system  (PO:0025205) that includes the totality of the portions of vascular tissue in their specific arrangement in an inflorescence (PO:0009049).
A primordium (PO:0025127) that develops from a root anlagen (PO:0025433) and is committed to the development of a root (PO:0009005).

definition.value: A root primordium may arise from cells of a pericycle (PO:0006203) in a root in most seed plant (pericyclic lateral root primordium; PO:0025492), from cells of an endodermis (PO:0000252) in ferns and some seed plants (non-pericyclic lateral root primordium: PO:0025493), or from cells of a shoot axis (PO:0025029), in the case of a basal root primordium (PO:0025479) or shoot-borne root primordium (PO:0025480). Transition from root primordium to root occurs with the formation of a root cap (PO:0020123), shortly after the development of a root apical meristem (PO:0020147).

value.value: A glandular trichome (PO:0004509) that synthesizes terpenophenolic resins and prenylflavonoids.

definition.value: One of the major chalconoids from hops is xanthohumol (CHEBI:66331).

value.value: A strobilus (PO:0025083) that bears only pollen (PO:0025281).
A strobilus (PO:0025083) that bears only plant ovules (PO:0020003).
A shoot lateral meristem (PO:0006344) that is part of a shoot axis (PO:0025029) and has a parts multiple layers of meristematic cells (PO:0004010) located near the shoot apical meristem (PO:0020148).

definition.value: Contributes to primary thickening of a shoot axis (PO:0025029), adventitious (shoot-borne) root (PO:0000042) formation, and formation of linkages between shot axis (PO:0000039), leaf (PO:0000036), and root (PO:0003011) vascular systems. Contiguous with the shoot apical meristem (PO:0020148) in some species, but not all. Produces more or less distinct vascular bundles (PO:0005020) surrounded by ground tissue (PO:0025059), as opposed to the more or less continuous xylem (PO:0005352) and phloem (PO:0005417) produced by a vascular cambium (PO:0005598). A primary thickening meristem is a multi-layered structure, compared to the single layer of a cambium. Found in many monocotyledons.

value.value: A portion of pith (PO:0006109) that is part of a root stele (PO:0020124).
A portion of pith (PO:0006109) that is part of a shoot axis (PO:0025029).

definition.value: Can occur in a stem or branch.

value.value: A portion of phloem (PO:0005417) tissue that develops from a vascular cambium (PO:0005598).

definition.value: Secondary phloem develops as part of secondary growth (GO:0080117).

value.value: A peripheral portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) in a plant axis (PO:0025004) that is composed of cork cambium (phellogen; PO:0005599), phellem (PO:0004003), and phelloderm (PO:0005050).

definition.value: After secondary growth, the periderm may replace the epidermis in stems and roots, rarely in other organs. In some cases, the epidermis is retained after periderm development. Periderm is derived from lateral meristem and may contain secondary phloem.

value.value: A portion of periderm tissue (PO:0005046) that is part of a root (PO:0009005).
A portion of periderm tissue (PO:0005046) that is part of a shoot axis (PO:0025029).

definition.value: Can occur on a stem or branch.

value.value: A portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) often resembling cortical parenchyma produced centripetally by the cork cambium.
A portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) that is the outermost layer of a portion of cortex (PO:0005708).

definition.value: A layer or layers of cells beneath the epidermis that is distinct in appearance from adjacent tissues.

value.value: A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) that consists of mass of undifferentiated plant cells (PO:0009002).

definition.value: Consists primarily of parenchyma cells but may contain other cell types as the callus begins to differentiate. May be formed as a result of wounding or may develop in culture.

value.value: A portion of shoot axis hypodermis (PO:0005057) that is part of a stem cortex (PO:0000223).

definition.value: Can occur in a stem or branch.

value.value: A portion of endodermis (PO:0000252) that is part of a shoot axis cortex (PO:0000223).

definition.value: Can occur in a stem or branch.

value.value: A portion of endodermis that is part of a root cortex.
A portion of endodermis that is part of a vascular leaf.

definition.value: Often found in the leaf of Gymnosperms and elsewhere.

value.value: A portion of vascular tissue (PO:0009015) that has as part one or more tracheary elements (PO:0000290).

definition.value: Functions in the translocation of water and solutes from roots (PO:0009005) to the shoot system (PO:0009006) and in support. Tracheary elements have lignified cell walls with secondary thickening and are dead at maturity.

value.value: A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) that is the outermost layer of endosperm (PO:0009089) in a seed (PO:0009010), its cells being characterized by presence of protein bodies (GO:0042735).

definition.value: Occurs in cereals and many other taxa. The protein bodies (GO:0042735) contain seed storage proteins and enzymes involved with endosperm digestion (Esau, 1977).

value.value: A portion of seed storage parenchyma that is part of an endosperm.

definition.value: Often devoid of intercellular spaces.

value.value: A portion of vascular tissue (PO:0009015) that has as parts sieve elements (PO:0025406).

definition.value: Functions in the conduction of organic substances in vascular plants.

value.value: A portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) composed of polyhedral cells typically with thin, non-lignified cellulosic cell walls and nucleate, living protoplasts.

definition.value: Parenchyma contains relatively unspecialized cells.

value.value: A portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) which comprises living tissue composed of more or less elongated cells with thick, non-lignified primary cell walls.
Chloroplast-containing parenchyma tissue.
A portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) which comprises supporting tissue composed of plant fiber cells (PO:0025407) or sclereid cells (PO:0025418).
A lateral meristem (PO:0020145) that has as part a single layer of cambial initial cells (PO:0000295) and their derivatives, arranged orderly in radial files.

definition.value: This term is applied to only two types of meristems: vascular cambium (PO:0005598) and cork cambium/phellogen (PO:0005599).

value.value: A cambium (PO:0005597) that is located between and gives rise to secondary xylem (PO:0005848) and secondary phloem (PO:0005043).

definition.value: A vascular cambium produces cells in both directions, centrifugally and centrifically, leading to an increase in the cross-sectional area of a plant axis (PO:0025004).

value.value: A cambium (PO:0005597) that is part of a periderm (PO:0005046) and produces phellem (PO:0004003) and phelloderm (PO:0005050).

definition.value: Cork cambium is located between the phellem and phelloderm and produces phellem toward the outside and phelloderm toward the inside of a plant axis (PO:0025004).

value.value: The chloroplast-containing, photosynthetic parenchymatous tissue situated between the two epidermal layers of the foliage leaf.

definition.value: If you are annotating to this term, please add an additional annotation to vascular leaf (PO:0009025) or non-vascular leaf (PO:0025075), depending on the species. All annotations for angiosperms, gymnosperms, and pteridophytes should go to vascular leaf and all annotations for bryophytes should go to non-vascular leaf.

value.value: Leaf mesophyll parenchyma characterized by little elongated cells, that are not closely packed and have conspicuous intercellular spaces.

definition.value: If you are annotating to this term, please add an additional annotation to vascular leaf (PO:0009025) or non-vascular leaf (PO:0025075), depending on the species. All annotations for angiosperms, gymnosperms, and pteridophytes should go to vascular leaf and all annotations for bryophytes should go to non-vascular leaf.

value.value: Parenchyma containing closely packed elongated chlorenchymatous cells oriented perpendicular to the leaf surface and which are active in photosynthesis.

definition.value: If you are annotating to this term, please add an additional annotation to vascular leaf (PO:0009025) or non-vascular leaf (PO:0025075), depending on the species. All annotations for angiosperms, gymnosperms, and pteridophytes should go to vascular leaf and all annotations for bryophytes should go to non-vascular leaf.

value.value: A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) that form specialized structures producing a secretion.

definition.value: The synonym gland does not imply non-secretory 'glands'.

value.value: A cardinal organ part that releases water through a hydathode pore.

definition.value: Hydathodes may have one or more pores that are similar to stomata but lack the ability to open and close. Hydathodes are involved in the release of water or xylem sap through pores via guttation or secretion. Generally, hydathodes are located at the end of a minor vein in a phyllome. In many plants, hydathodes includes a portion of thin-walled parenchyma between the tracheary elements and the pore, known as an epithem. In some plants, hydathodes are associated with secretory tissue.

value.value: A specialized tissue where excess salt absorbed in water from the soil is concentrated, being stores or excreted.

definition.value: A crust of salt forms on leaves which tastes bad and the white surfaces act to reflect light. Example, as is Mangrove vegetation.

value.value: A canal (PO:0025132) of schizogenous origin, lined with secretory resin cells (PO:0025604) and containing plant resin (PO:0025603).
A gland or a cavity lined with cells that secrete oils.

definition.value: Oil glands are schizogenous.

value.value: A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) composed of plant epidermal cells (PO:0004013) that develops from the protoderm (PO:0006210) and covers the surface of a plant structure (PO:0009011).

definition.value: The epidermis can be composed of one or more layers of cells. In some species of vascular plants, the epidermis, which is a primary tissue, is replaced by periderm, which is secondary tissue, later in development. The epidermis can also include trichomes, stomatal pores, root hairs, and rhizoids.

value.value: A portion of parenchyma tissue containing particularly large intercellular spaces of schizogenous or lysigenous origin.

definition.value: As applied to an intercellular space, originating by one or a combination of two processes, separation and degradation of cell walls.

value.value: A maximal portion of ground tissue (PO:0025059) between the vascular system (PO:0000034) and the epidermis (PO:0005679) in a plant.
The sub-epidermal layer or layers of cells of the root similar in structure and cytochemical characteristics of the endodermis, the outermost layer or layers of cells of the cortex.

definition.value: The cell walls are thickened and contain suberin. Absent in pteridophytes, fibrous in Phoenix and accompanied by sclerenchyma in Ananas.

value.value: A portion of xylem (PO:0005352) tissue that develops from a vascular cambium (PO:0005598).

definition.value: Secondary xylem develops as part of secondary growth (GO:0080117). Secondary xylem is the wood of gymnosperm and dicot angiosperm trees, shrubs, and lianas. May be organized into axial (PO:0025410) and ray (PO:0025411) systems. Secondary xylem is often part of a shoot axis (PO:0025029) or a root (PO:0009005) but may occur in other organs. Some monocots have a primary thickening meristem (PO:0005039), located near the shoot apical meristem (PO:0020148), that gives the appearance of secondary growth and may produce lignified tissue that appears woody but is not composed of secondary xylem. Tracheary elements in secondary xylem (PO:0000290) have lignified cell walls with secondary thickening and are dead at maturity.

value.value: A portion of xylem (PO:0005352) tissue that develops from the procambium (PO:0025275).

definition.value: Primary xylem develops as part of primary growth (request for primary growth has been made to GO) and is not differentiated into axial (PO:0025410) and ray (PO:0025411) systems. Tracheary elements (PO:0000290) have lignified cell walls with secondary thickening and are dead at maturity.

value.value: A collective phyllome structure that encloses a fruit of the Poaceae (caryopsis) and develops from a dried lemma and palea.
A lateral plant organ (PO:0009008) produced by a shoot apical meristem (PO:0020148).
A glume that is the proximal/basal of the two glumes subtending a pair of florets.
